25:17.683 --> 25:27.459 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Stay with us.

25:27.493 --> 25:32.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": Paul Ryan's first
major fight as speaker, to prevent a government

25:32.831 --> 25:37.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
shutdown; and Mark Shields and David Brooks
analyze this week's news.

25:37.302 --> 25:42.875 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, first, a new investigation that examines
casualties of the Cold War, and the scope

25:42.908 --> 25:48.280 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of those injured or killed while working with
or around nuclear material.

25:48.313 --> 25:53.919 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's the focus of a series of reports out
today from McClatchy News. Reporters in 10

25:53.952 --> 25:59.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
states spent a year chronicling and documenting
what happened to workers in the U.S. nuclear

25:59.725 --> 26:04.062 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
facilities from the 1940s right up until today.

26:04.096 --> 26:08.367 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has the story, and he recorded
this conversation a short time ago.

26:08.400 --> 26:12.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: McClatchy's team found the
federal government had never fully reveal

26:12.171 --> 26:16.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the true toll of what happened to men and
women working at nuclear facilities.

26:16.041 --> 26:21.547 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Back in 2001, the government set up a compensation
fund for some of those workers. The investigation

26:21.580 --> 26:26.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
found that more than 33,000 of them have died
from related illnesses. That's more than four

26:26.452 --> 26:30.322 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
times the number of Americans killed in the
Iraq and Afghanistan wars.

26:30.355 --> 26:35.494 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And there were more than 100,000 Americans
diagnosed with cancer and other diseases after

26:35.527 --> 26:39.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
helping to build the country's nuclear stockpile
over the decades.

26:39.498 --> 26:43.502 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lindsay Wise is one of the leading reporters
on the McClatchy team. She joins me now.

26:43.535 --> 26:45.170 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And welcome to you.

26:45.204 --> 26:49.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Want to fill in the picture first. What kind
of work and workers were most impacted, most

26:49.741 --> 26:51.376 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
exposed?

26:51.410 --> 26:52.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSAY WISE, McClatchy Washington Bureau:
Well, these were workers at plants, more than

26:52.377 --> 26:55.214 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
300 plants all over the country.

26:55.247 --> 27:02.087 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They did everything from pipe fitting and
production work, blue-collar work, to nuclear

27:02.120 --> 27:09.962 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
physicists and scientists. And we even found
in our database some CEOs who ran the contracting

27:09.995 --> 27:11.663 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
companies that managed the plant.

27:11.697 --> 27:17.302 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: You refer to this as a hidden
legacy. It's a little known casualty of the

27:17.336 --> 27:19.972 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Cold War, but how much was known?

27:20.005 --> 27:23.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSAY WISE: Well, this is what I found so
interesting working on this project, which

27:23.542 --> 27:28.113 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
was that I feel like when we talk about the
Cold War and the history of the Cold War,

27:28.146 --> 27:32.084 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we often talk about it as though it was a
war without any casualties, without any American

27:32.117 --> 27:33.719 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
casualties.

27:33.752 --> 27:38.023 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And what we were able to do at McClatchy is
we obtained a database from the Department

27:38.056 --> 27:42.794 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Labor for the compensation program, and
we were able to crunch the numbers and analyze

27:42.828 --> 27:48.467 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the data, and find the number of people who
had applied and then been compensated for

27:48.500 --> 27:50.402 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
illnesses and died.

27:50.435 --> 27:55.173 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so that told us that there were people
who gave their lives as part of the Cold War.

27:55.207 --> 27:59.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And within the scientific community,
within the government over the decades, how

27:59.711 --> 28:01.847 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
much awareness, how much study had been going
on?

28:01.880 --> 28:07.753 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSAY WISE: I think that, when this program
was created in 2001, there had been some awareness

28:07.786 --> 28:15.294 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Congress leading up to, and it was created
through the efforts of the Clinton administration

28:15.327 --> 28:18.196 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to compensate workers who had become ill.

28:18.230 --> 28:22.868 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It started to become apparent that many of
these workers had been exposed to dangerous

28:22.901 --> 28:27.039 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
subjects, radioactivity and other toxins,
without realizing it or without knowing the

28:27.072 --> 28:30.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
full extent of the health hazards that they
were facing.

28:30.342 --> 28:34.613 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so once that started to come to light
through some research of some reporters, The

28:34.646 --> 28:39.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Washington Post and other places, there was
pressure in Congress to pass a fund to compensate

28:39.484 --> 28:40.752 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the workers.

28:40.786 --> 28:43.322 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Now, you went and talked to
many of those workers.

28:43.355 --> 28:48.994 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you found a mix of pride in the work they
had done, right, but also bitterness in some

28:49.027 --> 28:51.296 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
cases over what they didn't know.

28:51.330 --> 28:56.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, you did -- we have a clip of one of the
workers. He's from the Hanford site. His name

28:56.234 --> 29:01.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is Tom Peterson. And he was exposed to levels
of beryllium. Explain first what beryllium

29:01.673 --> 29:03.075 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
is, and then we will watch that clip.

29:03.108 --> 29:06.511 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSAY WISE: Beryllium is a hazardous metal
used in weapons production.

29:06.545 --> 29:12.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it -- machined or worked with, it can
produce byproducts of dust that can be inhaled

29:12.250 --> 29:16.121 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by the workers. And there was a long time
where I don't think the full dangers of beryllium

29:16.154 --> 29:21.860 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were understood. And workers have been exposed
to this dust. And when they breathe it in,

29:21.893 --> 29:24.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there are some people who have an allergic
reaction.

29:24.129 --> 29:29.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And this creates scarring in their lungs,
so that they develop a -- many of them develop

29:29.568 --> 29:31.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a serious respiratory disease from that, that
can be fatal.

29:31.670 --> 29:33.739 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right, let's look at that
clip.

29:33.772 --> 29:41.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TOM PETERSON, Former Ironworker: I started
working in Hanford in 1978 as an ironworker.

29:41.780 --> 29:45.717 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nobody knew they were being exposed to beryllium
or what the consequences are.

29:45.751 --> 29:53.225 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MAN: So, the beryllium hazards were not well-recognized
early on. The problem is that some people

29:53.258 --> 29:56.194 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
are susceptible to very small amounts of beryllium.

29:56.228 --> 30:00.098 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TOM PETERSON: All of a sudden, I couldn't
finish mowing the lawn. I couldn't breathe.

30:00.132 --> 30:03.635 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Come to find out beryllium is all over the
Hanford site.

30:03.669 --> 30:09.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This legacy of beryllium contamination that
nobody knew anything about, they kept quiet

30:09.541 --> 30:15.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about. Your future is not real bright, but
it would have been nice to have been told

30:15.113 --> 30:18.717 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
about beryllium before we found out at a meeting.

30:18.750 --> 30:23.755 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Now, this compensation fund
has run into various kinds of criticism. Right?

30:23.789 --> 30:28.760 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's not enough, some people think. It's too
bureaucratic, some people think.

30:28.794 --> 30:34.099 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And on the other hand, there is some cases
where the suggestion is, there is overcompensation,

30:34.132 --> 30:36.468 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
because the direct link hasn't been proven.

30:36.501 --> 30:40.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSAY WISE: I think that in order for Congress
to create this compensation program, they

30:41.006 --> 30:47.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
did have -- the Department of Energy did have
to submit studies to show that workers in

30:47.546 --> 30:52.918 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the nuclear facilities around the country
were susceptible to higher rates of cancers

30:52.951 --> 30:55.387 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and non-malignant diseases.

30:55.420 --> 30:59.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
One of the things we did when we looked at
this data was, we really looked at the government's

30:59.825 --> 31:06.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
threshold for deciding a claim was valid that
it was more likely than not that a worker

31:06.832 --> 31:09.968 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
had gotten sick from something they did on
the job. And we used those numbers to come

31:10.001 --> 31:11.670 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
up with the death statistics.

31:11.703 --> 31:16.708 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Let me ask you, finally, you're
looking at past experience, but this is very

31:16.742 --> 31:21.546 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relevant still, right, because of a major
modernization program under way.

31:21.580 --> 31:27.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What lessons learned either by you or by -- more
importantly, I guess, by the government and

31:27.586 --> 31:29.921 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
by the people doing this kind of work still?

31:29.955 --> 31:34.326 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSAY WISE: Well, we took a look at not
just the workers from the past who worked

31:34.359 --> 31:38.630 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the Manhattan Project or the Cold War,
but also right up to the present day.

31:38.663 --> 31:46.738 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And what we found was that there were 186,000
workers in today -- since the program was

31:46.772 --> 31:53.678 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
created who work in weapons plants and research
facilities today that are -- had been exposed

31:53.712 --> 31:58.784 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to registerable levels of radiation just day
to day.

31:58.817 --> 32:04.222 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And some of those people have exceeded the
limit for -- that the Department of Energy

32:04.256 --> 32:09.728 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
had set as safe. Other workers we spoke to
were concerned that they were given -- they

32:09.761 --> 32:14.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
were told that their dosage from certain accidents
or exposures was a certain amount, but they

32:14.666 --> 32:19.571 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
felt that they were either being lied to or
that documents and records had been falsified.

32:19.604 --> 32:25.110 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we did find, when we reviewed contractor
misconduct, files that there were some cases

32:25.143 --> 32:30.215 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
where contractors had falsified radiation
records of workers right up until -- I think

32:30.248 --> 32:32.017 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the most recent case we looked at was 2013.

32:32.050 --> 32:34.653 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: So, an ongoing situation.

32:34.686 --> 32:35.887 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LINDSAY WISE: Mm-hmm.

32:35.921 --> 32:36.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Lindsay Wise of McClatchy News,
thanks so much.

32:36.488 --> 32:38.190 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LINDSAY WISE: Thank you.

32:38.223 --> 32:42.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Two key federal agencies responded
to the "NewsHour" after Jeff's interview.

32:42.794 --> 32:47.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Department of Energy praised workers for
their sacrifices and said its safety record

32:47.566 --> 32:52.637 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has improved due to better monitoring and
new protective limits at its sites and those

32:52.671 --> 32:54.339 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of its contractors.

32:54.372 --> 32:59.377 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Department of Labor said that its processing
of compensation claims is faster now, with

32:59.411 --> 33:04.716 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
many of the cases resolved within 180 days.
The department also said that it has paid

33:04.749 --> 33:14.793 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over $12 billion to more than 100,000 people
to -- quote -- "compensate for their suffering."

33:14.793 --> 33:23.468 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
over $12 billion to more than 100,000 people
to -- quote -- "compensate for their suffering."

33:23.501 --> 33:28.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now we turn to newly-elected speaker of the
House of Representatives, Republican Paul

33:28.373 --> 33:30.075 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Ryan.

33:30.108 --> 33:34.913 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He promises to overhaul internal House procedures,
giving rank-and-file members more say. And

33:34.946 --> 33:40.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
