33:42.320 --> 33:44.289 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Our political director, Lisa Desjardins, reports.

33:44.322 --> 33:48.293 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN (R-WI), Speaker of the House:
What's next?

33:48.326 --> 33:53.331 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Paul Ryan is on a roll. In
his first four working weeks, the new speaker

33:53.365 --> 33:59.938 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
presided over passage of a $600 billion defense
bill, a plan to tighten screening of Syrian

33:59.971 --> 34:06.311 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
refugees, and a five-year highway bill, the
types of big controversial bills that had

34:06.344 --> 34:09.347 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
been stuck in Capitol gridlock sometimes for
years.

34:09.381 --> 34:13.485 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN: I became speaker just over
a month ago, and I would like to think we

34:13.518 --> 34:18.723 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
have hit the ground running. We are dealing
with everything from highways, to ISIS, to

34:18.757 --> 34:20.325 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
funding the government.

34:20.358 --> 34:24.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: This wasn't the plan for
the 45-year-old from Wisconsin. He'd just

34:24.262 --> 34:29.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
started his dream job as chairman of the tax-writing
Ways and Means Committee. But the father of

34:29.234 --> 34:35.473 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
three young children agreed to become speaker,
thanks to two chaotic weeks when sharply divided

34:35.507 --> 34:38.143 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Republicans could not agree on anyone else.

34:38.176 --> 34:43.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN: Thursday was a great day.
Thursday was a day where we came together

34:43.515 --> 34:48.753 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as a conference and unified, and agreed to
proceed together with a vision.

34:48.787 --> 34:54.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And his vision is about ideas.
Ryan is a student of political philosophy,

34:54.426 --> 34:59.164 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
influenced by his mentor, the late conservative
Jack Kemp, who saw free markets and tax cuts

34:59.197 --> 35:05.804 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as the best antidotes to poverty, and Ayn
Rand, the divisive author who stressed individualism.

35:05.837 --> 35:10.675 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ryan is an admirer, but has been careful to
say he doesn't fully embrace her philosophy.

35:10.709 --> 35:15.680 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is a bootstraps conservative, setting out
to retool not just the Republican House, but

35:15.714 --> 35:17.415 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Republican agenda itself.

35:17.449 --> 35:23.254 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN: Put together a positive agenda,
and take it to the American people. Give the

35:23.288 --> 35:26.491 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
people of this country the choice that they
have been yearning for.

35:26.524 --> 35:31.696 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: But as Ryan aims to win Americans'
confidence, Democrats say he is dangerous.

35:31.730 --> 35:36.334 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. CHRIS VAN HOLLEN (D), Maryland: He is
more hard-edged ideologically than Speaker

35:36.368 --> 35:41.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Boehner was. Speaker Boehner was a rock-ribbed
-- rock-ribbed conservative. Paul Ryan had

35:41.906 --> 35:43.808 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
sharper ideological edges.

35:43.842 --> 35:49.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Congressman Chris Van Hollen
may be the Democrat who knows Ryan the best,

35:49.114 --> 35:53.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
after four years of working as his Democratic
counterpart on the House Budget Committee.

35:53.585 --> 35:58.490 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Van Hollen says Ryan's agenda is extreme,
including his Medicare plan that would end

35:58.523 --> 36:03.395 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the senior health care program as it exists
now and replace it with limited-amount vouchers.

36:03.428 --> 36:09.434 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. CHRIS VAN HOLLEN: It would do great damage
to Medicare. It would end the Medicare guarantee.

36:09.467 --> 36:14.239 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Ryan argues that, without
such changes, Medicare will go bankrupt. It's

36:14.272 --> 36:19.778 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a pragmatic, mathematical view. And that wins
him love from conservatives. But those same

36:19.811 --> 36:22.313 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
conservatives are also his biggest challenge.

36:22.347 --> 36:24.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. SEAN DUFFY (R), Wisconsin: This is Paul
Ryan's real first big test.

36:24.883 --> 36:28.620 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Fellow Wisconsin Congressman
Sean Duffy is talking about the government

36:28.653 --> 36:34.025 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
funding fight, a fight that is electrified
with red-hot conservative issues, including

36:34.059 --> 36:36.895 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Planned Parenthood funding and how to screen
refugees.

36:36.928 --> 36:41.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. SEAN DUFFY: These packages, they're never
great. They're big, they're long, they spend

36:41.966 --> 36:45.870 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a lot of money. This thing's going to stink
no matter the way you look at it, and Paul

36:45.904 --> 36:51.976 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ryan is going to have to make it smell as
rosy and lilacy as possible. We will see how

36:52.010 --> 36:53.878 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
well he does.

36:53.912 --> 36:58.383 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: This kind of battle has paralyzed
the House and its leaders for years. Do Republicans

36:58.416 --> 37:03.054 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
take a hard stance that they know the president
will block, risking a government shutdown,

37:03.088 --> 37:07.959 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or do they fund the government, at the expense
of their own values? Do they compromise or

37:07.992 --> 37:09.661 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
do they dig in?

37:09.694 --> 37:15.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. ILEANA ROS-LEHTINEN (R), Florida: That's
why sort of threading that needle in a very

37:15.166 --> 37:21.372 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
careful way. He's surfing his way through
some very big surf that our GOP Caucus is

37:21.406 --> 37:23.074 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
throwing at him.

37:23.108 --> 37:26.377 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Republican Congresswoman
Ileana Ros-Lehtinen believes Ryan is succeeding.

37:26.411 --> 37:30.081 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. ILEANA ROS-LEHTINEN: People are trusting
him. Yes, there's going to see how it all

37:30.115 --> 37:38.189 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
works out, but, as of now, even the most malcontent
and discontented Republican member, of which

37:38.223 --> 37:42.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we have a few -- you're never going to make
everybody happy -- has got to see that he's

37:42.760 --> 37:45.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
really trying his best to make the process
work.

37:46.030 --> 37:51.035 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And process is key. House
Speaker John Boehner was ousted, in part,

37:51.069 --> 37:56.074 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
due to complaints from conservatives who felt
that leadership ignored them. Now Ryan is

37:56.107 --> 37:57.775 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
changing House process.

37:57.809 --> 38:02.614 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
A few big items, giving members what's called
regular order. That means opportunities for

38:02.647 --> 38:07.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
everyone to propose and vote on more amendments,
and for committees, not party leaders, to

38:07.919 --> 38:14.526 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
drive debates. Also, to engage everyone, he
added one more all-member meeting each week.

38:14.559 --> 38:18.897 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Congressman Dave Brat was one of the unsure
conservatives who didn't vote for Ryan as

38:18.930 --> 38:21.132 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
speaker, but he says, so far, he is impressed.

38:21.166 --> 38:25.303 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. DAVE BRAT (R), Virginia: So, next year,
we anticipate regular order. That's a huge

38:25.336 --> 38:29.707 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
gain. I'm on the House Freedom Caucus. We
have been fighting for that and that bottom-up

38:29.741 --> 38:31.376 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
leadership.

38:31.409 --> 38:34.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: But in a time of threats
from Islamic State, concerns over immigration,

38:34.546 --> 38:40.952 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and continued job fears, process only goes
so far. Ryan is challenging his party to come

38:40.985 --> 38:42.554 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
up with a clear agenda.

38:42.587 --> 38:47.592 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN: If we want a mandate, then
we need to offer ideas. And if we want to

38:47.625 --> 38:49.761 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
offer ideas, then we need to actually have
ideas.

38:49.794 --> 38:55.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: As he pushes for new ideas,
Ryan is also tackling his party's identity

38:55.400 --> 39:00.705 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
now: pushing back against presidential GOP
front-runner Donald Trump, and Trump's call

39:00.738 --> 39:03.308 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to block Muslims from entering the United
States.

39:03.341 --> 39:09.013 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. PAUL RYAN: Normally, I do not comment
on what's going on in the presidential election.

39:09.047 --> 39:16.921 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I will take an exception today. This is not
conservatism. What was proposed yesterday

39:16.955 --> 39:23.061 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is not what this party stands for, and, more
importantly, it's not what this country stands

39:23.094 --> 39:24.829 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for.

39:24.862 --> 39:26.831 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
REP. ILEANA ROS-LEHTINEN: He's going to improve
our Republican brand. I hate to use that word

39:26.864 --> 39:34.205 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
brand, but that's the way people look at this
nowadays. And it's been tarnished, and we're

39:34.239 --> 39:37.342 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to earn that Good Housekeeping Seal
of Approval again.

39:37.375 --> 39:42.780 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Those are big national goals.
But first, of course, the new speaker must

39:42.814 --> 39:47.552 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
keep government running. The funding deadline
is just days away.

39:47.585 --> 39:51.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And Lisa joins us now from
Capitol Hill.

39:51.289 --> 39:55.960 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, Lisa, whatever Speaker Ryan is able to
get done this year, we know -- and you mentioned

39:55.994 --> 40:01.532 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it -- 2016 is an election year. Typically,
Congress practically grinds to a halt during

40:01.566 --> 40:02.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
election years.

40:02.200 --> 40:03.301 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

40:03.334 --> 40:05.069 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What are the expectations for
him then?

40:05.103 --> 40:07.272 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Well, I think Paul Ryan is
looking at this election year in a very different

40:07.305 --> 40:08.940 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
way from most speakers of the House, Judy.

40:08.973 --> 40:13.411 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I spoke to one of his senior aides tonight,
who said that Speaker Ryan thinks the party

40:13.444 --> 40:18.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
may not have a nominee until June or after,
and that that is way too long for the party

40:18.549 --> 40:22.887 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to wait to really spell out an agenda. So
here comes Speaker Ryan. He's ready to step

40:22.920 --> 40:28.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in and is planning to try and articulate some
policy, some proposals early next year, even

40:28.660 --> 40:30.595 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as Republicans are fighting for the White
House.

40:30.628 --> 40:34.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He could be wading into some tricky waters,
but even though Speaker Ryan is not running

40:34.799 --> 40:39.804 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
for president, it seems he could be a major
architect for whoever does become their candidate.

40:39.837 --> 40:44.108 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And just very quickly on this
budget shutdown, what does it look like? Are

40:44.142 --> 40:45.443 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
they going to keep the government open?

40:45.476 --> 40:47.178 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

40:47.211 --> 40:49.514 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, the lights are still on here. And they're
going to be on actually a lot this weekend.

40:49.547 --> 40:54.452 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There will be staffers around the clock this
weekend trying to work out dozens of still

40:54.485 --> 40:58.489 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hitches, different items that the two parties
need to agree on.

40:58.523 --> 41:02.493 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Next week, we will know a lot more. So far,
it looks like they could work this out. But,

41:02.527 --> 41:06.564 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Judy, while the deadline has been moved to
next Wednesday, I will make a little prediction.

41:06.597 --> 41:08.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It might get moved again. We will see.

41:08.366 --> 41:09.667 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: That would be a shock.

41:09.701 --> 41:10.301 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

41:10.335 --> 41:11.169 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Imagine.

41:11.202 --> 41:12.904 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Lisa Desjardins, thank you.

41:12.937 --> 41:14.605 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: My pleasure.

41:14.639 --> 41:18.209 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And now to the analysis of
Shields and Brooks. That's syndicated columnist

41:18.242 --> 41:21.245 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Mark Shields and New York Times columnist
David Brooks.

41:21.279 --> 41:22.146 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome, gentlemen.

41:22.180 --> 41:25.450 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, let's talk about Paul Ryan for minute.

41:25.483 --> 41:27.085 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Mark, how is he doing?

41:27.118 --> 41:32.423 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: He's doing fine, Judy, until
-- this is a test coming up, of course, with

41:32.457 --> 41:34.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the budgeting, keeping the federal government
open.

41:35.026 --> 41:41.332 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's got a certain honeymoon period. And I
think he's been the beneficiary. First of

41:41.366 --> 41:45.370 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
all, he has to deal with the Freedom Caucus
and the conservatives who were the bane of

41:45.403 --> 41:46.170 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
John Boehner.

41:46.204 --> 41:47.004 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

41:47.038 --> 41:48.606 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The bane of John Boehner.

41:48.639 --> 41:56.080 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: And I think he's benefited,
in a strange way, by the chaos created by

41:56.114 --> 41:57.715 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Donald Trump.

41:57.749 --> 42:02.687 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He looks, in comparison, by -- a grownup.
And I think, at the same time, that, for the

42:02.720 --> 42:06.657 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
first time, there is nervousness and anxiety
among Republicans that they could lose their

42:06.691 --> 42:08.726 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
congressional majorities next November.

42:08.760 --> 42:16.934 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there is less tolerance, perhaps, for
all the hissy fits and tantrums that have

42:16.968 --> 42:18.970 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
been thrown by House members in the past.

42:19.003 --> 42:20.338 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Contrast with Boehner?

42:20.371 --> 42:22.006 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: It is.

42:22.039 --> 42:24.375 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
First of all, I have to say there are very
few successful Republican beards. And I think

42:24.409 --> 42:26.511 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he's pulling it off. So, that's very important
to the brand.

42:26.544 --> 42:27.979 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

42:28.012 --> 42:30.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Not since Lincoln, maybe, have
we had a good Republican beard.

42:30.314 --> 42:33.684 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But he -- the way you believe something is
as important as what you believe. What Chris

42:33.718 --> 42:36.821 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Van Hollen said in that piece, that he is
more conservative than John Boehner, that

42:36.854 --> 42:43.995 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is certainly true. But he is more communicative.
He's also just warmer. And he's ostentatiously

42:44.028 --> 42:45.797 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
respectful to other people.

42:45.830 --> 42:49.934 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so just that manner has helped him. It's
also helped him, frankly, that Boehner did

42:49.967 --> 42:53.371 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a lot of the heavy lifting on the government
shutdown stuff before he left, on raising

42:53.404 --> 42:57.008 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the spending caps and some of that other stuff,
so it will be a lot easier. And that's a tribute

42:57.041 --> 43:00.611 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to what Boehner did before he walked out the
door there.

43:00.645 --> 43:05.516 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then the devolution of power is just big.
You are managing an organization. And you

43:05.550 --> 43:09.520 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
give some people some control over what they're
doing. I would say, since I came to Washington,

43:09.554 --> 43:14.025 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in almost every institution, power has grown
more and more centralized, either in the White

43:14.058 --> 43:18.029 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
House or in Congress or in agencies, smaller
zones of trust.

43:18.062 --> 43:21.365 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so to reverse that is kind of revolutionary
and kind of impressive.

43:21.399 --> 43:27.972 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, if you look at -- as David
just said, you're looking at Paul Ryan as

43:28.005 --> 43:32.777 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
someone who is more conservative than the
leadership the Republicans had before, so

43:32.810 --> 43:36.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you would think there would be more push and
pull, but it looks like he's trying to get

43:36.814 --> 43:37.882 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
things done.

43:37.915 --> 43:39.584 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, he is trying to get things
done.

43:39.617 --> 43:45.823 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it comes down to the continuing resolution.
This is the maximum power that a minority

43:45.857 --> 43:51.863 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
who are in opposition or have a particular
case, a cause or point of view, for them to

43:51.896 --> 43:55.199 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
exercise it and to influence the threat.

43:55.233 --> 44:00.137 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Republicans could not have a shutdown
of the government right now. They can't. And

44:00.171 --> 44:02.173 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
so he's got to limit...

44:02.206 --> 44:03.875 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why not? Why not?

44:03.908 --> 44:09.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, because this is a party
that, quite frankly, right now is on the cusp

44:09.413 --> 44:15.386 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of a nervous breakdown, I think it's fair
to say, with the Trump candidacy and what's

44:15.419 --> 44:19.690 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going on and just the rhetoric in that whole
debate.

44:19.724 --> 44:27.798 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You heard Ileana Ros-Lehtinen say in her piece
to Lisa the Republican brand, that she looks

44:27.832 --> 44:34.338 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to Paul Ryan to save the Republican brand,
which is damaged. And so he's got to get that

44:34.372 --> 44:42.747 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
done. So -- and this is the time where you
bring up riders. Riders are the last children,

44:42.780 --> 44:46.250 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
really, of special legislation.

44:46.284 --> 44:47.852 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
There's not supposed to be a rider on appropriations.

44:47.885 --> 44:49.253 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: These are issues that are separate
from...

44:49.287 --> 44:50.922 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:50.955 --> 44:51.856 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: They're not supposed to be on
appropriation, but everybody wants to bring

44:51.889 --> 44:52.757 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
up his cause right now.

44:52.790 --> 44:53.791 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Yes.

44:53.824 --> 44:55.660 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: And so that's the problem he
faces.

44:55.693 --> 44:59.163 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He's got to get it done. They want to see
him succeed. And they don't want him to fail.

44:59.196 --> 45:05.069 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He does have one great advantage. And that
is that he didn't plot and scheme to get this

45:05.102 --> 45:10.274 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
job. It was really thrust upon him. So I think
that's an advantage, that he didn't crawl

45:10.308 --> 45:13.578 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
all over -- crawl over carcasses and corpses
to get there.

45:13.611 --> 45:17.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: When it comes to Trump, David,
I know we have been talking about him, but

45:17.515 --> 45:22.853 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this week, with the statement about keeping
Muslims out of the country, is this just more

45:22.887 --> 45:26.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of the same of what we have been hearing from
Donald Trump, or are we hearing something

45:26.390 --> 45:27.658 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
at a completely new level?

45:27.692 --> 45:29.894 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: I think it's a different level.

45:29.927 --> 45:33.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The man is a genius for attention, an addict
of attention, and therefore a genius of getting

45:33.764 --> 45:40.671 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it. And so this I think is a different level
for a couple of reasons. First, it is bigotry

45:40.705 --> 45:45.509 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of a naked sort. The Mexican stuff was bigotry,
too, but this strikes me as a higher level.

45:45.543 --> 45:50.748 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Second, an offense against religious liberty.
And, third, because of the way Trump has now

45:50.781 --> 45:54.919 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
risen to prominence, it has reverberations
around the globe, in the way the stuff even

45:54.952 --> 45:58.022 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
he said earlier about Latin Americans didn't.

45:58.055 --> 46:04.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so it's done enormous damage to America's
reputation abroad. And so I do it's something

46:04.261 --> 46:08.899 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
different. Politically, it's a total winner.
I mean, let's be clear. The polls show it,

46:08.933 --> 46:10.568 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and for a number of reasons.

46:10.601 --> 46:13.571 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
People, as we heard earlier in the program,
are scared about terrorism. Secondly, there

46:13.604 --> 46:20.277 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has been a pent-up, silent frustration about
political correctness. So anybody who says

46:20.311 --> 46:25.449 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
something politically completely incorrect,
and properly incorrect, for some people, that's

46:25.483 --> 46:28.586 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
like a liberation. It's, finally, somebody's
saying the truth.

46:28.619 --> 46:33.424 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so he's benefiting from that. And so it's
right now a total winner on the Republican

46:33.457 --> 46:35.059 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
primary.

46:35.092 --> 46:39.330 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And if it's a winner -- and,
Mark, the polls do show that -- I think I

46:39.363 --> 46:45.369 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
saw 40-some percent of Republicans agree with
his statement.

46:45.403 --> 46:49.640 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But when you talk about the electorate overall,
it's only about 20-something percent.

46:49.674 --> 46:51.342 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
MARK SHIELDS: Yes.

46:51.375 --> 46:56.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No, it's a real problem for the Republicans,
Judy. It's a problem for the country. I mean,

46:56.514 --> 47:05.056 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we saw it this week. Karl Rove, George Bush's
amanuensis, his master strategist, said that

47:05.089 --> 47:12.697 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- wrote that the nomination of Donald Trump
is a gift to the Democrats and would doom

47:12.730 --> 47:14.331 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the Republicans.

47:14.365 --> 47:19.537 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We saw 20 Republican leaders, as reported
by Robert Costa in The Washington Post, had

47:19.570 --> 47:25.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a secret meeting, that they were that concerned,
that anxious to somehow provoke and guarantee

47:25.276 --> 47:31.248 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that there will be a brokered convention in
Cleveland next summer to do anything, apparently,

47:31.282 --> 47:34.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
to deny him the nomination.

47:34.218 --> 47:40.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What he did this week, with -- talked about
as being intemperate, or being outrageous,

47:40.257 --> 47:47.531 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or ethnic slurs -- this really, to use a term
I'm reluctant to use, was un-American. I mean,

47:47.565 --> 47:52.636 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
religious tolerance is in the citizenship
papers of this country. It was put there by

47:52.670 --> 48:02.646 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thomas Jefferson and James Madison, specifically
to include Jews and nonbelievers and Muslims.

48:02.680 --> 48:09.553 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It wasn't -- so that it wasn't simply Christians
or Protestants of a certain sectarian -- and

48:09.587 --> 48:16.961 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
so, I mean, this was just -- this was really
so offensive and so outrageous. I mean, when

48:16.994 --> 48:21.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- and I thought the timid and rather tepid
reaction of a lot of Republicans -- when Dick

48:21.999 --> 48:28.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Cheney becomes the moral templar of your party
to say this is unacceptable, and I think a

48:28.806 --> 48:34.812 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
word has to be said on behalf of both Cheney
and George W. Bush, that, after 9/11, they

48:34.845 --> 48:40.818 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
deliberately, consciously didn't bring any
-- made sure that this would have a religious

48:40.851 --> 48:44.722 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
element to it, the war in Iraq, the ill-fated
war in Iraq.

48:44.755 --> 48:49.460 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What effect -- David, you said,
short-term, it helps him politically, but

48:49.493 --> 48:55.499 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
what effect is it having on this race? How
is it changing the shape of this presidential...

48:55.533 --> 48:57.201 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
DAVID BROOKS: Yes.

48:57.234 --> 48:59.537 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, first, on the Republican Party, it doesn't
-- not -- looking at the data, it doesn't

48:59.570 --> 49:04.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
seem to be bleeding over into hurting the
Republican brand. If you look at the party

49:04.241 --> 49:07.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
approval, it pretty much where it was. It's
slightly up where it was three or four months

49:07.144 --> 49:08.913 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ago.

49:08.946 --> 49:13.384 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
People may disapprove of Donald Trump, but,
so far, they don't see him as a typical Republican,

49:13.417 --> 49:17.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
maybe because he's running against the party.
I continue to believe -- and I will believe

49:17.488 --> 49:21.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to my dying day -- that he will -- his numbers
will collapse. I have said it here on a weekly

49:21.725 --> 49:25.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
basis, and I don't think any of this matters
until the final months.

49:25.863 --> 49:27.364 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But events like Paris...

49:27.398 --> 49:29.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: We're getting close.

49:29.066 --> 49:32.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: We're getting close. And events
like Paris -- and his genius for attention

49:32.303 --> 49:37.541 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- what he does is, he takes a concrete issue
or a broad issue which is complicated and

49:37.575 --> 49:42.813 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he turns it into sometimes brutal and sometimes
horrific simplicity.

49:42.847 --> 49:49.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so there is this broad fear of security
and terrorism. He -- specifically Muslims,

49:49.687 --> 49:53.390 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and that, like, lodges in people's minds as
something simple and bold, and somehow he

49:53.424 --> 49:56.493 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
seems to some people like a strong leader.

49:56.527 --> 49:59.997 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you hate women? The question that was asked
to him in one of the debates. No, just Rosie

50:00.030 --> 50:06.103 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
O'Donnell. How much money are you worth? He
could say 6.8 million -- he says $10 billion.

50:06.136 --> 50:11.508 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there's a genius for attention by turning
everything into concrete, very specific things

50:11.542 --> 50:17.214 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that lodge in the mind. And that is a demagogic
genius, but let's face it, he has it.

50:17.248 --> 50:21.886 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I still think the electorate will turn, but
he is not to be underestimated for that demagogic

50:21.919 --> 50:23.587 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ability.

50:23.621 --> 50:27.858 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Mark, you said a minute ago
that Republicans had -- some Republicans hadn't

50:27.892 --> 50:32.830 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
been strong enough in their disagreeing or
denouncing what Trump said about Muslims.

50:32.863 --> 50:38.969 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But it's been interesting to watch Ted Cruz,
senator from Texas. He's one who seems to

50:39.003 --> 50:45.142 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be rising in the public opinion polls. What
is it that he's saying? And his statement

50:45.175 --> 50:49.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about Trump, if I got it correctly, was, I
don't agree with him, but he has a right to

50:49.914 --> 50:51.582 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
say that.

50:51.615 --> 50:55.185 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then there was, I guess, the story that
came out today or yesterday where, in private,

50:55.219 --> 50:59.957 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
he said he thinks Trump is going to collapse,
but then -- Trump later shot back, and Cruz

50:59.990 --> 51:01.825 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
said, oh, Trump's terrific.

51:01.859 --> 51:03.627 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But how do you explain Ted Cruz?

51:03.661 --> 51:06.864 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Well, if you want to know what
a candidate really thinks, you tape him in

51:06.897 --> 51:13.103 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
an off-the-record fund-raising meeting. And
that's where Ted Cruz did say that, that he

51:13.137 --> 51:21.679 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
didn't think Donald Trump had the judgment
to survive and to win the presidency.

51:21.712 --> 51:27.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Ted Cruz has just been right up to Donald
Trump's left shoulder. Donald Trump insinuates,

51:27.785 --> 51:34.591 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
as David puts it, that Barack Obama may not
be a total American because he won't say radical

51:34.625 --> 51:40.731 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Muslim terrorist, or extremist, and he won't
use that term, he won't, in other words, give

51:40.764 --> 51:45.269 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it the religious component, and he says, there
is something going on there, he says.

51:45.302 --> 51:52.676 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Well, Ted Cruz calls him an apologist for
radical Islam instead. Now, it's one thing,

51:52.710 --> 51:57.314 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Judy, if I disagree with you and say you're
mistaken or you're ill-informed. When I start

51:57.348 --> 52:03.287 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
demonizing your motives -- and he does that.
He does that in speech. He's sort of Donald

52:03.320 --> 52:11.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Trump with better academic credentials, a
better haircut and probably 60 I.Q. points.

52:11.261 --> 52:12.663 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

52:12.696 --> 52:14.631 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, other than that, what
would you add about Ted Cruz?

52:14.665 --> 52:17.568 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: Well, Cruz is interesting because
he's universally unpopular.

52:17.601 --> 52:19.203 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARK SHIELDS: Universally.

52:19.236 --> 52:24.208 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID BROOKS: In the law firm, at school,
among the Republicans -- when he was working

52:24.241 --> 52:28.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
with George W. Bush's campaign, he could not
get a serious job after that, because everyone

52:28.078 --> 52:29.713 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
said, I will not work with that guy.

52:29.747 --> 52:33.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He comes to the Senate, Republican senators,
if they had a vote between some Democrat to

52:33.784 --> 52:37.354 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be majority leader and Ted Cruz, they would
vote for the Democrat. He is just unpopular.

52:37.388 --> 52:42.159 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And he's used that unpopularity to his benefit
in this campaign. Look, they all hate me.

52:42.192 --> 52:45.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And so, if you're running an anti-Washington
campaign, the fact that everyone who works

52:45.496 --> 52:47.698 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
with you hates you suddenly becomes a plus.

52:47.731 --> 52:52.102 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The other interesting is, for a guy who runs
on principle, he's extremely tactical. He's

52:52.136 --> 52:57.107 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
very deft at moving this way and that. And
so the Republican Party faces this problem,

52:57.141 --> 53:01.111 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that they don't want Trump, but the alternative
might be Cruz, and they don't want that either.

53:01.145 --> 53:06.817 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And we will leave it on that
note, David Brooks, Mark Shields.

53:06.850 --> 53:10.454 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And we have a reminder about some programs
to come from our PBS colleagues.

53:10.487 --> 53:14.691 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Gwen Ifill is preparing for "Washington Week,"
which airs later this tonight. Here's a preview:

53:14.725 --> 53:21.398 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: For better or worse, Donald Trump
has transformed the nature of the 2016 presidential

53:21.432 --> 53:26.970 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
campaign. Tonight, our roundtable tackles
what that means for politics, for policy,

53:27.004 --> 53:31.675 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and for the way Americans see themselves,
tonight on "Washington Week" -- Judy.

53:31.708 --> 53:37.247 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Then, on tomorrow's "PBS NewsHour
Weekend": how an investment in wind power

53:37.281 --> 53:41.318 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has helped put Denmark on the path to energy
independence.

53:41.351 --> 53:42.820 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's the "NewsHour" for tonight.

53:42.853 --> 53:47.224 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
On Monday, we examine the results of the Paris
climate talks.

53:47.257 --> 53:50.727 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I'm Judy Woodruff. Join us online, and again
right here tomorrow evening.

53:50.761 --> 53:54.431 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
From all of us at the "PBS NewsHour," have
a great weekend. Thank you, and good night.
